ese ruminations summon a range of cultural companions, including El Greco, Emily Dickinson, Judy Garland, Wallace Stevens, Edgar Allan Poe, William Morris, and Rachel Carson. While brilliantly portraying nature’s sublime energy, Horn also confronts issues of consumption, destruction, and loss, as the industrial and man-made encroach on Icelandic wilderness.Filled with musings on a secluded region that perpetually encourages a sense of discovery, Island Zombie illuminates a wild and beautiful Iceland that remains essential and new.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 7aART / Individual Artists / Artists' Books.2bisacsh  aA Field Guide to Getting Lost.  aAnthropocene.  aArctic circle.  aEudora Welty.  aGlenn Gould.  aIceland.  aIcelandic.  aJules Verne.  aKerlingarfjoll.  aLydia Davis.  aMorgunbladid.  aRebecca Solnit.  aReykjavik.  aRobert Macfarlane.  aRobert Smithson.  aThe Wild Places.  aartist's books.  aartist's notebook.  aartist's writings.  aautobiography.  aclimate change.  aclimate.  acollected writings.  aconceptual.  adyrholaey.  aenvironmental issues.  aessays.  aexperiential.  afirst-person narrative.  ageology.  ageothermal.  ageysers.  aglacier.  aisland.  aisolation.  alandscape.  alighthouses.  aliterature.  alyric.  ameditation.  amigration.  amotorcycles.  apastoral.  apoetry.  apools.  aseclusion.  asolitude.  aswimming pools.  athe elements.  athe environment.  atoilets.  avolcanoes.  awater.  aweather.  awind.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertArt and Architecture eBook-Package 2020z978311073823008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069008840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691208978?locatt=mode:legacy40uht